  <text>
    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Fordhook Weddy. 2 o'clock</p>
      <p>Dearest &amp; sweetest Mate. I have very little to say to ou, except that I miss ou very much, &amp; find my nest exceedingly lonely at night.-- I suppose you are now just about sitting down to dinner, where I imagine you</p>
      <p>will hear the Earl and Countess's health drunk.</p>
      <p>The Hen seems not to get accustomed as yet to the Lovelace Bird, &amp; often calls her by her old name.-- On Friday we are to lunch in Town (St James' Sqre), &amp; go on to Tunbridge Wells in the afternoon. I suppose it is double post to Tunbridge, so arrange as you think</p>
      <p>best about the letters, but if possible, I want to hear every day. Should you write tomorrow, it must be to St. James' Sqre, unless it is to Tunbridge, as we shall have left Fordhood before the post comes in at Acton.--</p>
      <p>I am very well today, &amp; soon recovered my flurry yesterday afternoon.</p>
      <p>Dr Locock was as usual very kind to the little</p>
      <p>fluttering bird, &amp; staid about 1/4 of an hour I think after ou went, fanning her.-- I said something when he went away, as delicately as I could, in allusion to the fees which in strictness are due to him, but he instantly turned his back &amp; said "I wish Your Ladyship Good Morning", &amp; abruptly left the room.</p>
      <p>The Hen tells me that during Mr. Lushington's illness last year, he never took a single fee, and</p>
    </div></body>
